.TH "HTMLElement.toggle_event" "JS" "July 26, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLElement.toggle_event \- HTMLElement: toggle event
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]toggle\f[B]\f[R] event of the \f[CR]HTMLElement\f[R]
interface fires on a popover element (i.e.\ one that has a valid
\f[CR]popover\f[R] attribute) just after it is shown or hidden.
.IP \[bu] 2
If the popover element is transitioning from hidden to showing, the
\f[CR]event.oldState\f[R] property will be set to \f[CR]closed\f[R] and
the \f[CR]event.newState\f[R] property will be set to \f[CR]open\f[R].
.IP \[bu] 2
If the popover element is transitioning from showing to hidden, then
\f[CR]event.oldState\f[R] will be \f[CR]open\f[R] and
\f[CR]event.newState\f[R] will be \f[CR]closed\f[R].
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] The \f[CR]toggle\f[R] event behaves differently when
fired on \f[CR]<details>\f[R] elements.
In this case, it does not relate to popovers, and instead fires when the
\f[CR]open\f[R]/\f[CR]closed\f[R] state of a \f[CR]<details>\f[R]
element is toggled.
See the \f[CR]HTMLDetailsElement\f[R] \f[CR]toggle\f[R] event page for
more information.
.RE
.SH SYNTAX
Use the event name in methods like \f[CR]addEventListener()\f[R], or set
an event handler property.
.IP
.EX
addEventListener(\[dq]toggle\[dq], (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {});

ontoggle = (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {};
.EE
.SH EVENT TYPE
A \f[CR]ToggleEvent\f[R].
Inherits from \f[CR]Event\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic example
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] popover = document.getElementById(\[dq]mypopover\[dq]);

\f[I]// ...\f[R]

popover.addEventListener(\[dq]toggle\[dq], (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (event.newState === \[dq]open\[dq]) {
    console.log(\[dq]Popover has been shown\[dq]);
  } \f[B]else\f[R] {
    console.log(\[dq]Popover has been hidden\[dq]);
  }
});
.EE
.SS A note on toggle event coalescing
It is worth pointing out that \f[CR]toggle\f[R] events are coalesced,
meaning that if multiple \f[CR]toggle\f[R] events are fired before the
event loop has a chance to cycle, only a single event will be fired.
.PP
For example:
.IP
.EX
popover.addEventListener(\[dq]toggle\[dq], () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]//...\f[R]
});

popover.showPopover();
popover.hidePopover();
\f[I]// \[ga]toggle\[ga] only fires once\f[R]
.EE
